ChatGPT said:
Great question ğŸ‘ â€” the answer depends on how you plan to use the Azure Compute Gallery (ACG).

Letâ€™s break it down:

ğŸ”¹ When to use a Generalized Image in ACG
Use case: You want a golden base image to deploy many VMs (scale sets, dev/test, prod replicas).

Requirements:

OS must be generalized (Sysprep for Windows, waagent -deprovision+user for Linux).

Azure VM Agent must be installed.

What happens on deployment:

Azure injects new username/password/SSH keys.

Hostname, extensions, identity â†’ all configured fresh.

Pros:

Reusable across environments.

Recommended by Microsoft for scale-out scenarios.

Cons:

You lose user/data config during sysprep/deprovision.

ğŸ‘‰ This is the most common choice for production workloads.

ğŸ”¹ When to use a Specialized Image in ACG
Use case: You want to preserve the state of an existing VM (migration, lift-and-shift, DR).

Requirements:

No need to generalize.

VM Agent is optional (but useful for monitoring/extensions).

What happens on deployment:

VM boots with the exact same OS, accounts, and configs as the source.

Azure cannot reset username/SSH keys â€” you must use the original ones.

Pros:

Faster (no need to rebuild or sysprep).

Great for stateful workloads or legacy apps.

Cons:

Not ideal for scaling out many VMs.

Harder to maintain long term.

ğŸ‘‰ This is best for migration or DR scenarios.

ğŸ”‘ Rule of Thumb
If you are building reusable, golden images â†’ Use Generalized âœ…

If you are preserving state of an existing VM â†’ Use Specialized âœ…

âš¡ In your case:
Since you uploaded a ready-made VHD and it works as a bootable managed disk, if you want it to behave the same in ACG â†’ you should use a Specialized image.
But if your goal is to use it as a base image for multiple VMs â†’ you should convert it into a Generalized image.

